      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 30-year-old G2P1 woman at 38 weeks gestation, diagnosed with Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy (ICP), presents with severe pruritus. Her recent blood tests show serum bile acid levels >40 &mu;mol/L. What is the next step in management?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "DT1193445",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 1193445,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Intrahepatic Cholestasis of Pregnancy (ICP)</strong> is associated with increased risks of <strong>intrauterine fetal demise</strong>, especially when <strong>serum bile acid levels exceed 40 &mu;mol/L</strong>.</p>\n<p>According to <strong>protocol</strong>, labour<strong> is induced at 38 weeks</strong> if:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Symptoms worsen, or</li>\n<li>Bile acids &gt;40 &mu;mol/L<br /> (Ruled out option <strong>D</strong>)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid and Cholestyramine do not address the immediate fetal risk. (Ruled out options<strong> A &amp; C)</strong></p>",
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
